  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in serious criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum of 30 years if the laundering involves specific financial transactions\n\n2. Substantial financial penalties:\n- Fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Criminal forfeiture of assets used in or derived from illegal activities\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Asset seizure\n- Permanent criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\nSpecific penalties depend on factors like transaction amount, intent, criminal history, and whether the offense involves other underlying crimes.\n\nThe primary federal statute governing money laundering is 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956, which outlines various money laundering offenses and corresponding penalties.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering penalties?",
